<div class="prose">

<p><strong>U5's signature AI partner.</strong> A perspective-taking coach that role-plays specific stakeholders in water-rights disputes — Tamil Nadu Cauvery delta farmer, Karnataka upstream farmer, Bengaluru urban consumer, Adivasi community member, downstream fisherman, environmental NGO, Cauvery Water Management Authority representative, and so on. Makes the <em>strongest</em> version of any stakeholder's argument so students rehearse responding to well-formed positions rather than caricatures.</p>

{% include "partials/partner-launch.njk" %}

<h2>Overview — why this partner is uniquely valuable</h2>
<p>The Position Paper's whole T/T centerpiece is <strong>arguing from a perspective that isn't your own default</strong>. That's hard to do without a partner who can play the perspective convincingly back at you. The Stakeholder Voice does that. It names whichever stakeholder you specify — for whichever case — and gets into character: their interests, the evidence they cite, the framing they use, the concerns they raise. Then you argue with them. The partner is making the <em>strongest</em> version of the stakeholder's argument because weak arguments don't help you rehearse — only strong, well-formed positions force you to develop substantive responses.</p>
<p>The second move the partner makes — and this is the signature one — is <strong>flagging when you're projecting your own framing onto the stakeholder instead of genuinely arguing from theirs</strong>. Most students don't notice when they do this; the Stakeholder Voice does. "That's actually your own view talking, not your stakeholder's. Their version of that argument would sound more like…" is the partner's most useful intervention.</p>

<h2>Trial-aware: three different ways this partner exists</h2>
<p>Unit 5 runs in three pedagogical arms (see the <a href="/units/unit-5/">Unit 5 landing</a>). The Stakeholder Voice exists in different forms depending on your section — the same skill, three scaffolds:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Section A (BoodleBox)</strong>: <em>You build your own.</em> The Boodle Build Assignment guides you through constructing a custom AI bot for your chosen stakeholder — 8-section system prompt template covering identity, beliefs, strongest argument, what they refuse to give up, what they honestly admit, how they describe opponents, evidence they cite, and constraints. Iterate with 5 test questions + ≥2 revision cycles. Peer Boodle test in Block 8. <strong>Building the bot is the deepest possible way to learn the perspective</strong> — because you had to specify, in writing, exactly what they would think, want, defend, and refuse.</li>
  <li><strong>Section B (Flint)</strong>: Pre-built Flint Stakeholder Voice tutors. Mr. Ignash configures the stakeholder personas; you work with the pre-built version. Linear scaffolding, consistent voice across stakeholders. You push for the strongest version; the Flint tutor delivers it.</li>
  <li><strong>Section C (paper-based)</strong>: No AI. You work from the paper Stakeholder Profile Pack — 7 detailed Q&amp;A interview profiles per case, composite voices based on real positions. Same perspective-taking skill, via close reading + interview-style preparation rather than AI dialogue.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Pairs with</h2>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">The Hydrologist</a></strong> — different roles, complementary. The Stakeholder Voice handles perspective-taking on top of the dispute; the Hydrologist handles the water-systems science underneath. If you ask the Stakeholder Voice a hydrology question, it'll redirect you to the Hydrologist — staying in character means not pretending to be a neutral expert on the science.</p>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/the-skeptic/">The Skeptic</a></strong> — for stress-testing your stakeholder's position before the Block 9 Roundtable. The Stakeholder Voice plays one opposing stakeholder at a time; the Skeptic surfaces broader weaknesses in your own position (logical gaps, evidence problems, untested assumptions).</p>

